# =============================================================================
# Elastic Beanstalk environment configuration.
#
# THE ACTUAL FIX FOR THE 502 BAD GATEWAY ERROR
# ----------------------------------------------
# An earlier version of this file set the `PORT` environment property,
# reasoning that EB's built-in nginx reverse proxy (which forwards
# port-80 traffic to port 5000 by default) just needed to be told to
# forward to this app's port (8000) instead. That reasoning was wrong for
# this deployment, and didn't fix the 502.
#
# Why: EB's built-in nginx proxy — the one the `PORT` property configures
# — only exists for the *single-container* Docker platform. This project
# deploys via `docker-compose.yml` (EB auto-detects this and treats it as
# a "Docker Compose" / multi-container deployment), and per AWS's own
# docs, that proxy is disabled entirely in that mode:
#
#   "Even if you select NGINX as a proxy server, this setting is ignored
#    in an environment with Docker Compose. The Proxy server setting
#    still defaults to None... Since the NGINX web server proxy is
#    disabled for the Docker on Amazon Linux 2 platform with Docker
#    Compose..."
#   — https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticbeanstalk/latest/dg/create_deploy_docker.container.console.html
#
# With no proxy in front, EB's load balancer / instance listener sends
# traffic directly to port 80 on the EC2 instance (confirmed by AWS's own
# Docker Compose quickstart, whose example `docker-compose.yml` publishes
# its front-facing container to host port 80 explicitly — nothing does
# that for you automatically). Our `api` service was instead publishing
# to host port 8000, so nothing was listening on port 80 → 502.
#
# The real fix lives in `docker-compose.yml`: the `api` service now
# publishes `"${HOST_PORT:-8000}:8000"` instead of a hardcoded
# `"8000:8000"`. HOST_PORT below overrides that to "80" specifically for
# this EB environment (local `docker compose up` is unaffected — it still
# defaults to port 8000, no sudo required).
#
# How HOST_PORT reaches docker-compose.yml: EB auto-generates a file
# literally named `.env` at the application's root directory from every
# property set here under `aws:elasticbeanstalk:application:environment`
# (confirmed via AWS's docs on "Environments with Docker Compose"). Since
# `docker-compose.yml` lives in that same root directory, Docker Compose's
# own built-in variable-interpolation feature picks that `.env` file up
# automatically — no `env_file:` directive or other wiring needed for
# HOST_PORT specifically (that's a separate, additional mechanism, used
# elsewhere in docker-compose.yml to pass variables *into containers* at
# runtime — interpolation into the YAML itself, like `${HOST_PORT:-8000}`
# in a `ports:` mapping, is resolved before that even happens).
#
# The Application Healthcheck URL setting below is a secondary, related
# fix: this API has no route at `/` (only `/api/v1/...` and
# `/api/v1/health`), so Elastic Beanstalk's own health check — which
# defaults to requesting `/` — would otherwise see 404s from an
# otherwise-perfectly-healthy environment. Pointing it at the app's
# purpose-built liveness endpoint avoids that false signal.
# =============================================================================
option_settings:
  aws:elasticbeanstalk:application:environment:
    HOST_PORT: "80"
  aws:elasticbeanstalk:application:
    Application Healthcheck URL: /api/v1/health
